  "body": "## Issue\r\n\r\nMulti-line import statements in Solidity don't work with contracts in npm modules.\r\n\r\n## Steps to Reproduce\r\n\r\n1. Create a new Truffle project.\r\n2. Install OpenZeppelin: `npm install --save-dev @openzeppelin/contracts` or `yarn add --dev @openzeppelin/contracts`\r\n3. Set solc version to 0.6.8 (to be able to use latest OpenZeppelin)\r\n4. Add the following contract code `Foo.sol`:\r\n```solidity\r\npragma solidity ^0.6.0;\r\n\r\nimport {\r\n  ReentrancyGuard\r\n} from \"@openzeppelin/contracts/utils/ReentrancyGuard.sol\";\r\n\r\ncontract Foo is ReentrancyGuard {\r\n}\r\n```\r\n5. `truffle compile`.\r\n\r\n## Expected Behavior\r\n\r\nShould work fine.\r\n\r\n## Actual Results\r\n\r\n```\r\ncontracts/Foo.sol:3:1: ParserError: Source \"@openzeppelin/contracts/utils/ReentrancyGuard.sol\" not found: File import callback not supported\r\nimport {\r\n^ (Relevant source part starts here and spans across multiple lines).\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf the import statement is in a single line, then it works fine, but it should work regardless of whether it's multi-line or single-line. Importing a local file also works fine regardless of linebreaks.\r\n```solidity\r\nimport { ReentrancyGuard } from \"@openzeppelin/contracts/utils/ReentrancyGuard.sol\";\r\n```\r\n\r\nPopular code formatters like `prettier` would split the statement because it's too long for the default line width of 80.\r\n\r\n## Environment\r\n\r\n* Operating System: \r\n`Linux ubuntu 5.4.0-33-generic #37-Ubuntu SMP Thu May 21 12:53:59 UTC 2020 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux`\r\n* Ethereum client: N/A\r\n* Truffle version (`truffle version`): v.5.1.27\r\n* node version (`node --version`): v12.17.0\r\n* npm version (`npm --version`): v6.14.4\r\n",
